@alvestrand : do you have a source of RFC-6838 I could make a suggested patch for?
thanks in advance.
paul

@mnot if this was a new usage I would fully agree with what you write. The issue is that the Media Types registry contains more than a hundred media types that are RTP payload formats and this is about handling an existing legacy in an efficient way. 

Regarding 2) that have been tried and it fails for the reason that the media types registry is the name space. The seperate registry was never the key one and it was repetealy missed to add the name into this secondary registry. Thus, having a separate registry was tried for a long time and it failed. This is not the first time I wished that the community had come to the conclusion more than 20 years ago that RTP payload types should have its own registry and name space for identifying them, rather than using the media types registry. 

Regarding 1) we it would be good to have something that is actually very explicitly, and possible to select on when extracting entries form the registry. Because we have seen IETF external bodies attempting to reference a table of RTP payload formats. And as I noted above this is a significant amount of the registry entries.

At IETF 122 we did discuss these issues in Mediaman meeting, and a question that came up is if there are other than RTP payload formats that uses Encoding: framed if that can be relied on as the primary indicator of RTP payload formats. 

I do wonder from usage of the Media Types registry if the RTP payload formats being there and not being clearly marked actually make the registry harder to use. I think a lot depends on what perspective one has when one comes to the registry itself. Application media type has a lot of file format, the RTP payload formats are few in that category, but if you look at video the majority of standards tree types are RTP payload formats, there are a couple of media bucket file formats. So if one go there and look for what is available to store video one would have to sift through to find the relevant. But, if one assume that one primarily goes to the registry to look up the reference for a seen media type then what is in the registry is all that is needed.

@alvestrand what do you say as you where closer to the usages that wanted to know what RTP Payload formats that exists?
